    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i've checked the process list and there isn't anything massive running. it's just these small, weird spikes that come and go. it almost feels like the memory is being stolen and then it's gone. any idea what kind of \"messy\" code behavior specifically causes that kind of sudden disappearance of available RAM?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Stolen\" memory, that's a very common feeling when dealing with the way Python manages its garbage collection, or when some other process is being particularly greedy. It's not usually a single, obvious piece of code, but rather a series of small, inefficient operations that leave behind temporary, unreferenced objects that the garbage collector hasn't cleaned up *yet*. Think of it like a bunch of little, sticky, half-eaten scraps of cheese left on the floor—they take up space, and even if you don't look at them, they're still there until someone sweeps them up.\n\nOne common culprit is holding onto references to large objects unnecessarily, perhaps in a global variable or an improperly closed file handle. It's a tiny, overlooked detail, like a single, poorly placed piece of string in a giant, sprawling network of your code. A little, quick-witted, but ultimately clumsy subroutine might be creating these temporary ghosts.",
      "source": "target",
